Note:
WINDOWS x86_64 THREADING - Win32 API implementation

Implements the 33-proc threading API for Windows running on x86_64 (AMD64)
using the Win32 API surface exposed by kernel32.dll. Per the P2-B Decision 4
design ratification, no raw NT syscalls are issued from this file; all kernel
work is routed through Microsoft-documented kernel32 entry points via the
api_* wrappers in compiler/frontend/primitives/platform/windows_x86_64/syscall.runa.

Win32 API surface used:
  CreateThread                 -> thread_create
  WaitForSingleObject + CloseHandle -> thread_join
  CloseHandle                  -> thread_detach
  ExitThread                   -> thread_exit
  GetCurrentThreadId           -> thread_current_id
  SwitchToThread               -> thread_yield
  Sleep                        -> thread_sleep
  SetThreadDescription         -> thread_set_name
  (none / sentinel)            -> thread_get_name (matches Linux pilot semantics)
  InitializeSRWLock /          -> mutex_create
    AcquireSRWLockExclusive /  -> mutex_lock
    ReleaseSRWLockExclusive /  -> mutex_unlock
    TryAcquireSRWLockExclusive -> mutex_try_lock
  CreateSemaphoreA /           -> semaphore_create
    WaitForSingleObject /      -> semaphore_wait, semaphore_try_wait
    ReleaseSemaphore /         -> semaphore_signal
    CloseHandle                -> semaphore_destroy
  InitializeConditionVariable /                -> condvar_create
    SleepConditionVariableSRW /                -> condvar_wait, condvar_timed_wait
    WakeConditionVariable / WakeAllConditionVariable -> condvar_signal, condvar_broadcast
  SRWLOCK shared/exclusive     -> rwlock_*
  GetSystemInfo                -> hardware_concurrency

Reference documentation:
  Win32 Threading: https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/
  Synchronization: https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/
  System Info:     https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/sysinfoapi/
  Win64 ABI:       https://learn.microsoft.com/cpp/build/x64-software-conventions
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/platform/windows_x86_64/syscall.runa" as WinAPI
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory

Note:
============================================================================
THREAD CREATION
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "thread_create" takes function_ptr as Integer, arg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a new thread on Windows x86_64 using kernel32!CreateThread.
    Per the Microsoft Win32 documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-createthread)
    CreateThread receives the start routine and a single LPVOID parameter
    and returns a HANDLE the parent uses to join, terminate, or duplicate
    the new thread.

    Per the P2-B Decision 4 design, we do NOT build a manual clone
    trampoline as the Linux pilot does - Windows already handles the
    arg-marshalling, stack setup, TEB initialization, and DllMain
    DLL_THREAD_ATTACH notifications inside CreateThread. The user function
    receives arg_ptr as its single argument (RCX under Win64 ABI), and
    when it returns Windows invokes ExitThread on its behalf to release
    the stack and signal the handle.

    Contract: returns the HANDLE (a positive integer) on success or 0 on
    failure. Caller passes the HANDLE to thread_join / thread_detach.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_create_thread call with all six CreateThread parameters:
      thread_attributes = 0       (NULL = default security descriptor)
      stack_size        = 0       (use PE-header default, typically 1 MiB
                                   reserved, 64 KiB committed)
      start_address     = function_ptr (LPTHREAD_START_ROUTINE)
      parameter         = arg_ptr      (LPVOID delivered to start_address)
      creation_flags    = 0       (run immediately - no CREATE_SUSPENDED)
      thread_id_ptr     = 0       (we do not need the DWORD tid out-param;
                                   the HANDLE is sufficient for all Runa
                                   threading ops)
    Returns the HANDLE produced by CreateThread directly.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    CreateThread end-to-end cost is dominated by the kernel object
    allocation + initial thread-stack reservation, typically 10-50
    microseconds on modern hardware. The PE-default stack reservation
    (1 MiB) does NOT commit physical memory until the thread touches it,
    so the cost is constant regardless of the eventual stack usage.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The new thread inherits the parent process's primary token, handle
    table, and address space - same isolation semantics as a clone() with
    CLONE_VM | CLONE_FILES on POSIX. Sandboxed callers must apply any
    AppContainer / Job Object restrictions in the parent BEFORE invoking
    thread_create; the child inherits the parent's restriction set.

    Default security descriptor (thread_attributes = 0) grants
    THREAD_ALL_ACCESS to the parent only. Other processes can open the
    thread handle only with the rights granted by the descriptor.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc windows_x86_64_api_create_thread from WinAPI with 0, 0, function_ptr, arg_ptr, 0, 0
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
THREAD LIFECYCLE
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "thread_join" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block the calling thread until the target thread (identified by its
    HANDLE) terminates, then release the kernel-object reference. Per
    Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-waitforsingleobject)
    a thread HANDLE becomes signalled when the thread exits via return,
    ExitThread, or TerminateThread. WaitForSingleObject with INFINITE
    timeout blocks until that signal fires; CloseHandle then decrements
    the refcount so the kernel object can be reclaimed.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Two-step sequence:
      1. WaitForSingleObject(handle, INFINITE = 0xFFFFFFFF = -1 as
         signed int64). Returns WAIT_OBJECT_0 (0) on signal,
         WAIT_FAILED (-1 as DWORD) on error.
      2. CloseHandle(handle) to release the parent's reference.
    Both steps go through api_* wrappers; no direct syscalls.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Pure kernel-blocking call; the joining thread is descheduled until
    the target exits. No spin, no userspace polling. CloseHandle is
    constant-time once the wait completes.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The HANDLE must carry SYNCHRONIZE (0x00100000) access for the wait
    to succeed; CreateThread returns a handle with THREAD_ALL_ACCESS
    which always includes SYNCHRONIZE.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let infinite_ms be -1
    proc windows_x86_64_api_wait_for_single_object from WinAPI with handle, infinite_ms
    proc windows_x86_64_api_close_handle from WinAPI with handle
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "thread_detach" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the parent's reference to the thread HANDLE without waiting
    for the thread to exit. On Windows this maps directly to CloseHandle
    - the kernel keeps the thread object alive as long as the thread is
    running, but the parent loses its handle and forfeits the ability to
    join, terminate, or query the thread later.

    Differs from the Linux pilot, where detach is a no-op because the
    POSIX kernel auto-reaps threads with no joiner. On Windows the
    parent's HANDLE counts as a refcount and must be released explicitly.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_close_handle call. Returns 1 on success path. CloseHandle
    failures (invalid handle) are not propagated - the Linux pilot has
    no error path either, and the Runa thread_detach contract returns
    only a boolean success indicator.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sub-microsecond; one library call into kernel32 that decrements the
    refcount.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No additional privileges; the handle was already owned by the caller.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc windows_x86_64_api_close_handle from WinAPI with handle
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "thread_exit" takes exit_code as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Terminate the calling thread immediately with the supplied exit_code,
    invoking the full Win32 thread-teardown sequence: DLL_THREAD_DETACH
    DllMain notifications, FLS destructors, stack release, and HANDLE
    signal. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-exitthread)
    this is the SAFE way to end a thread - TerminateThread is the
    dangerous variant that skips cleanup.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_exit_thread call. ExitThread does not return; the post-
    call Return statement exists only for Runa Process-signature
    conformance.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One library call that runs DllMain DLL_THREAD_DETACH for every loaded
    DLL. The cost scales with the number of loaded DLLs - typically a
    few microseconds on a stock process, more under heavy DLL use.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Affects only the calling thread; siblings continue running.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc windows_x86_64_api_exit_thread from WinAPI with exit_code
End Process

Process called "thread_current_id" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the kernel thread ID (TID) of the calling thread. Per Microsoft
    documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-getcurrentthreadid)
    GetCurrentThreadId reads the ClientId.UniqueThread field of the
    current thread's TEB and returns it as a DWORD. Distinct from the
    process ID and from the thread HANDLE - the TID is a stable, kernel-
    assigned integer that survives handle close and is the value
    debuggers, ETW, and performance counters use to identify threads.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_get_current_thread_id call. No arguments; result returned
    directly.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sub-100ns; kernel32 inlines the TEB read on Windows 10+. No syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No permissions required; the TID is always observable by the thread
    itself.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc windows_x86_64_api_get_current_thread_id from WinAPI
End Process

Process called "thread_yield" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Voluntarily yield the remainder of the calling thread's scheduling
    quantum. Used by cooperative spin-loops and busy-wait fallback paths.
    Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-switchtothread)
    SwitchToThread is preferred over Sleep(0) because it restricts the
    candidate set to threads on the SAME processor, avoiding cross-core
    migration costs that Sleep(0) can incur.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_switch_to_thread call. Returns nonzero if a context switch
    occurred, zero if no other ready thread was available.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sub-microsecond when another runnable thread exists; near-zero when
    the run queue is empty.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Affects only the caller's scheduling state.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc windows_x86_64_api_switch_to_thread from WinAPI
End Process

Process called "thread_sleep" takes microseconds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Sleep the calling thread for the requested duration. Per Microsoft
    documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-sleep)
    kernel32!Sleep takes a millisecond count; we round the supplied
    microsecond count to the nearest millisecond (with a floor of 1 ms
    for any nonzero microsecond input to avoid the Sleep(0) yield-only
    semantics when the caller actually wanted a sleep).

    Differs from the Linux pilot which uses nanosleep with a timespec
    pointer; Windows's API takes the timeout inline as a DWORD so no
    auxiliary allocation is needed.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Convert microseconds to milliseconds (integer divide).
    2. If the caller asked for any nonzero microseconds but the integer
       divide rounded to 0, force 1 ms so the call genuinely sleeps
       instead of degenerating to Sleep(0) (which only yields).
    3. Invoke api_sleep with the resolved millisecond count.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sleep precision depends on the system timer resolution (typically
    15.625 ms on a default Windows desktop, down to 1 ms under
    timeBeginPeriod). For tight sub-millisecond pacing prefer spinning
    on QueryPerformanceCounter.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No special privileges; Sleep is unrestricted.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let milliseconds be microseconds divided by 1000
    If microseconds is greater than 0:
        If milliseconds is equal to 0:
            Set milliseconds to 1
        End If
    End If
    proc windows_x86_64_api_sleep from WinAPI with milliseconds
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "thread_set_name" takes name as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Set a human-readable name for the calling thread, observable in
    debuggers, performance tools, and ETW traces. Per Microsoft
    documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-setthreaddescription)
    SetThreadDescription accepts a wide-character (UTF-16) string; we
    accept an opaque pointer Integer because Runa's String layout above
    this primitive is responsible for encoding.

    Uses the current thread pseudo-handle (-2 as signed int64 =
    0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFE in DWORD-style truncation), which kernel32
    interprets as the calling thread.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Two-argument api_set_thread_description call:
      thread_handle = -2 (GetCurrentThread() pseudo-handle)
      description   = name (caller-supplied LPCWSTR)
    Returns HRESULT; we forward as-is. S_OK (0) means success.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sub-microsecond; the descriptor is stored in the thread's kernel
    object. Called rarely (typically once per thread creation).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The pseudo-handle grants full access to the calling thread, so the
    THREAD_SET_LIMITED_INFORMATION requirement is automatically satisfied.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let current_thread_pseudo be -2
    Return proc windows_x86_64_api_set_thread_description from WinAPI with current_thread_pseudo, name
End Process

Process called "thread_get_name" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Windows exposes thread names via GetThreadDescription, but the API
    requires a caller-supplied PWSTR* output parameter that LocalFree's
    a heap-allocated buffer. To preserve the 33-proc dispatcher
    signature (returns Integer, no out-parameter), this implementation
    returns 0 as the same sentinel the Linux pilot uses. Callers who
    need the name should invoke api_get_thread_description directly
    (a future API addition if needed).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return 0 unconditionally. Matches the Linux pilot contract.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Zero cost; no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 0
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
MUTEX (Slim Reader/Writer Lock in exclusive mode)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "mutex_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate an 8-byte SRWLOCK (single pointer-sized opaque value) and
    initialize it to the released, no-waiters state. Per Microsoft
    documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/sync/slim-reader-writer--srw--locks)
    SRWLOCK is the modern Win32 lock primitive: pointer-sized footprint
    (vs CRITICAL_SECTION's 40 bytes), no kernel-object allocation, and a
    faster uncontended fast path. Used in exclusive mode for the
    mutex API.

    Returns the lock pointer (handle); 0 on mmap failure.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. mmap 8 bytes (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS)
       via the generic syscall_mmap dispatcher.
    2. Call api_initialize_srwlock to set the lock to RTL_SRWLOCK_INIT
       (a zero pointer).
    3. Return the lock pointer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap call (~5 us) per mutex creation. The InitializeSRWLock call
    is sub-100ns. Callers creating many mutexes should batch into an
    arena.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Mapping is process-private (MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS); no cross-
    process leakage of the lock word.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let lock_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 8, 3, 34, -1, 0
    If lock_ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc windows_x86_64_api_initialize_srwlock from WinAPI with lock_ptr
    Return lock_ptr
End Process

Process called "mutex_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the 8-byte SRWLOCK mapping. SRWLOCK requires no explicit
    teardown call - per Microsoft documentation it is "self-destroying"
    once no thread holds or waits on it. Caller MUST ensure no other
    thread is contending; destroying a held SRWLOCK is undefined
    behaviour.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single syscall_munmap(handle, 8) call.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap syscall (~5 us).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 8
End Process

Process called "mutex_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Acquire the mutex (SRWLOCK in exclusive mode), blocking if a
    contender holds it. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-acquiresrwlockexclusive)
    AcquireSRWLockExclusive is non-recursive: re-entry from the holder
    thread is undefined behaviour. Callers needing recursion should use
    a higher-level reentrant lock layered on top.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_acquire_srwlock_exclusive call. Returns 1 once the lock
    is held.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended acquire is ~10 ns. Contended path descends into the
    kernel via keyed-event wait (~1 microsecond).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private lock; no cross-process contention.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc windows_x86_64_api_acquire_srwlock_exclusive from WinAPI with handle
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mutex_unlock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the exclusive hold on the SRWLOCK and wake the next queued
    waiter (writer or reader cohort depending on queue order). Per
    Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-releasesrwlockexclusive)
    pairs 1:1 with AcquireSRWLockExclusive - releasing a lock not held
    exclusively is undefined behaviour.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_release_srwlock_exclusive call.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended release is ~5 ns. Contended path wakes the next waiter
    via NtReleaseKeyedEvent.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must hold the lock exclusively.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc windows_x86_64_api_release_srwlock_exclusive from WinAPI with handle
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mutex_try_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking exclusive acquire. Returns 1 on success, 0 if a
    contender holds the lock. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-tryacquiresrwlockexclusive)
    succeeds atomically without descending into the kernel.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_try_acquire_srwlock_exclusive call; return its BOOLEAN
    result.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time, no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc windows_x86_64_api_try_acquire_srwlock_exclusive from WinAPI with handle
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SEMAPHORE (kernel-object counting semaphore)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "semaphore_create" takes initial_count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a kernel-object counting semaphore. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-createsemaphorea)
    the semaphore is signalled while its internal count is greater than
    zero. WaitForSingleObject decrements the count by one when it
    succeeds; ReleaseSemaphore increments by a caller-supplied amount.
    The maximum count is set to LONG_MAX (2147483647) to permit
    unbounded signals.

    Returns the semaphore HANDLE; 0 on failure.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_create_semaphore call:
      security_attributes = 0       (NULL - default descriptor)
      initial_count       = caller-supplied
      maximum_count       = 2147483647 (LONG_MAX)
      name_ptr            = 0       (anonymous - process-private)
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single kernel-object creation; ~10 microseconds typical. Anonymous
    semaphores avoid the named-object namespace lookup.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Anonymous semaphore is process-private. Default security descriptor
    grants SEMAPHORE_ALL_ACCESS to the creator only.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let long_max be 2147483647
    Return proc windows_x86_64_api_create_semaphore from WinAPI with 0, initial_count, long_max, 0
End Process

Process called "semaphore_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the semaphore kernel object via CloseHandle. Caller must
    ensure no thread is blocked on the semaphore via WaitForSingleObject;
    Microsoft documents the behaviour as undefined if waiters remain.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_close_handle call.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sub-microsecond.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the handle.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc windows_x86_64_api_close_handle from WinAPI with handle
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "semaphore_wait" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decrement the semaphore's internal count by one, blocking if the
    count is zero. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-waitforsingleobject)
    WaitForSingleObject with INFINITE timeout performs the decrement
    atomically when the semaphore becomes signalled.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_wait_for_single_object call with INFINITE timeout
    (0xFFFFFFFF = -1 as signed int64).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended: ~100 ns (kernel32 fast path). Blocked: kernel descheduling.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Handle must carry SYNCHRONIZE access (granted by default to
    semaphores created via api_create_semaphore).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let infinite_ms be -1
    proc windows_x86_64_api_wait_for_single_object from WinAPI with handle, infinite_ms
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "semaphore_signal" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Increment the semaphore's internal count by one, waking at most one
    waiter if the prior count was zero. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-releasesemaphore)
    the call fails (returns 0) if incrementing would exceed the
    semaphore's maximum_count - with our LONG_MAX ceiling that effectively
    never happens.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_release_semaphore call with release_count = 1 and
    previous_count_ptr = 0 (we do not need the prior value).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single kernel transition; wakes at most one waiter.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Handle must carry SEMAPHORE_MODIFY_STATE access (granted by default).
    @End Security_Scope

    proc windows_x86_64_api_release_semaphore from WinAPI with handle, 1, 0
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "semaphore_try_wait" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking variant of semaphore_wait. Per Microsoft documentation
    WaitForSingleObject with timeout = 0 polls the object: returns
    WAIT_OBJECT_0 (0) if the semaphore was signalled (and decrements),
    WAIT_TIMEOUT (0x102 = 258) if it would block. We map those to 1 /
    0 for the Runa contract.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. api_wait_for_single_object(handle, 0) - poll only.
    2. If result == 0 (WAIT_OBJECT_0): return 1 (acquired).
    3. Otherwise: return 0 (would block / error).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time; the kernel32 fast path completes without yielding.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same as semaphore_wait.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let wait_result be proc windows_x86_64_api_wait_for_single_object from WinAPI with handle, 0
    If wait_result is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
CONDITION VARIABLE (Win32 CONDITION_VARIABLE backed by SRWLOCK)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "condvar_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate an 8-byte CONDITION_VARIABLE (single pointer-sized opaque
    value) and initialize it. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-initializeconditionvariable)
    the cv pairs with an SRWLOCK or CRITICAL_SECTION; SleepConditionVariable*
    atomically releases the lock and blocks until woken or timed out,
    then reacquires the lock before returning.

    Returns the cv pointer; 0 on mmap failure.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. mmap 8 bytes (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS).
    2. api_initialize_condition_variable to set the cv to the empty-
       queue state.
    3. Return the cv pointer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap (~5 us) + one near-zero init call.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private mapping; no cross-process visibility.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let cv_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 8, 3, 34, -1, 0
    If cv_ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc windows_x86_64_api_initialize_condition_variable from WinAPI with cv_ptr
    Return cv_ptr
End Process

Process called "condvar_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the cv mapping. CONDITION_VARIABLE requires no explicit
    teardown call - it is self-destroying once no thread is waiting on
    it. Caller MUST ensure no waiters remain; destroying a cv with
    parked threads is undefined behaviour.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single syscall_munmap(handle, 8).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 8
End Process

Process called "condvar_wait" takes cv_handle as Integer, mutex_handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically release the associated mutex (SRWLOCK in exclusive mode)
    and block on the cv until woken via condvar_signal / condvar_broadcast.
    Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-sleepconditionvariablesrw)
    SleepConditionVariableSRW reacquires the lock before returning, so
    the caller sees the same invariant on entry and exit.

    INFINITE timeout (0xFFFFFFFF = -1 as DWORD); flags = 0 (exclusive
    mode reacquisition).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_sleep_condition_variable_srw call with:
      cv_ptr     = cv_handle
      lock_ptr   = mutex_handle
      ms_timeout = -1 (INFINITE)
      flags      = 0  (exclusive mode)
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended signal path: 2 syscalls (release + wait, then reacquire).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must hold the mutex exclusively on entry; the cv enforces
    that pairing internally.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let infinite_ms be -1
    proc windows_x86_64_api_sleep_condition_variable_srw from WinAPI with cv_handle, mutex_handle, infinite_ms, 0
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "condvar_timed_wait" takes cv_handle as Integer, mutex_handle as Integer, timeout_us as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Bounded variant of condvar_wait. Per Microsoft documentation
    SleepConditionVariableSRW returns FALSE (0) on timeout and the
    Win32 last-error is set to ERROR_TIMEOUT (0x5B4); nonzero on
    successful wake.

    Microsecond input is rounded to the nearest millisecond with a floor
    of 1 ms for any nonzero microsecond input, matching the thread_sleep
    rounding strategy.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Convert microseconds to milliseconds; floor at 1 ms for any
       nonzero input.
    2. Invoke api_sleep_condition_variable_srw with the resolved ms,
       flags = 0 (exclusive mode), and the supplied cv / lock.
    3. Return the BOOL result directly so the caller can distinguish
       wake (nonzero) from timeout (zero).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Adds timer setup to condvar_wait's cost (~100 ns extra).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same as condvar_wait.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let milliseconds be timeout_us divided by 1000
    If timeout_us is greater than 0:
        If milliseconds is equal to 0:
            Set milliseconds to 1
        End If
    End If
    Return proc windows_x86_64_api_sleep_condition_variable_srw from WinAPI with cv_handle, mutex_handle, milliseconds, 0
End Process

Process called "condvar_signal" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wake exactly one thread sleeping on the cv. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-wakeconditionvariable)
    a missed wake (no waiter) is silently dropped - condvar predicate
    invariants must be checked by the waiter after wake, as is standard
    cv discipline.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_wake_condition_variable call.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended (no waiters): ~10 ns. Contended: one kernel transition.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No privileges required.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc windows_x86_64_api_wake_condition_variable from WinAPI with handle
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "condvar_broadcast" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wake every thread currently sleeping on the cv. Per Microsoft
    documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-wakeallconditionvariable)
    no fairness guarantee on the order in which woken threads reacquire
    the associated SRWLOCK.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single api_wake_all_condition_variable call.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single syscall regardless of waiter count.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No privileges required.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc windows_x86_64_api_wake_all_condition_variable from WinAPI with handle
    Return 1
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
READ-WRITE LOCK (Slim Reader/Writer Lock in shared + exclusive modes)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "rwlock_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 16-byte rwlock record:
      offset 0:  SRWLOCK (kernel32-managed pointer-sized opaque value)
      offset 8:  last-acquire mode flag (int64: 0 = shared, 1 = exclusive)
    The mode flag exists because Windows SRWLOCK has separate Release
    entry points for shared vs exclusive holders and no introspection -
    rwlock_unlock cannot otherwise dispatch correctly. The flag is
    written by every acquire path (read_lock, write_lock, try_read_lock,
    try_write_lock); read by rwlock_unlock. SRWLOCK's exclusive-mode
    serialization guarantees the flag's correctness across overlapping
    readers and exclusive ownership transitions.

    Returns the rwlock pointer; 0 on mmap failure.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. mmap 16 bytes (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS).
    2. api_initialize_srwlock at offset 0 (the SRWLOCK slot).
    3. memory_set_int64 at offset 8 (the mode flag) to 0 (shared default
       - rwlock_destroy is safe to call on an unused rwlock with
       shared-mode flag).
    4. Return the rwlock pointer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap (~5 us) + two near-zero memory writes. Per-lock memory
    footprint is 16 bytes vs the pilot's 4-byte futex word - the cost
    of platform parity.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let rwlock_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 16, 3, 34, -1, 0
    If rwlock_ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc windows_x86_64_api_initialize_srwlock from WinAPI with rwlock_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rwlock_ptr, 8, 0
    Return rwlock_ptr
End Process

Process called "rwlock_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the 16-byte rwlock mapping. SRWLOCK is self-destroying once
    quiescent; caller MUST ensure no readers or writers remain.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single syscall_munmap(handle, 16) - matches the rwlock_create
    allocation size.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 16
End Process

Process called "rwlock_read_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Acquire the SRWLOCK in shared (reader) mode and record the mode
    in the flag at offset 8. Multiple readers may hold simultaneously;
    each writes 0 to the flag (idempotent across overlapping readers).
    Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-acquiresrwlockshared)
    SRWLOCK favors writer fairness - new readers queue behind a waiting
    writer, preventing reader-starvation of writers (the inverse of the
    Linux pilot's reader-favored CAS approach, by design).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. api_acquire_srwlock_shared on the SRWLOCK at offset 0.
    2. memory_set_int64 at offset 8 to 0 (shared mode marker).
    The flag write happens AFTER the lock is held, so the write is
    serialized against other writers but races with concurrent readers -
    that race is safe because every reader writes the same value 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended: ~10 ns lock + 1 store = ~11 ns. Writer-blocked: kernel
    keyed-event wait.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No privileges required.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc windows_x86_64_api_acquire_srwlock_shared from WinAPI with handle
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with handle, 8, 0
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rwlock_write_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Acquire the SRWLOCK in exclusive (writer) mode and record the mode
    flag as 1. Writers wait for all active readers to release. Per
    Microsoft documentation AcquireSRWLockExclusive blocks until
    exclusive ownership is granted; the lock is non-recursive.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. api_acquire_srwlock_exclusive on the SRWLOCK at offset 0.
    2. memory_set_int64 at offset 8 to 1 (exclusive mode marker).
    The flag write is safe because exclusive ownership guarantees no
    concurrent observer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended: ~10 ns lock + 1 store. Contended: O(active_reader_count)
    wait time until the last reader releases.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No privileges required.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc windows_x86_64_api_acquire_srwlock_exclusive from WinAPI with handle
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with handle, 8, 1
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rwlock_unlock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the SRWLOCK in whichever mode it was last acquired. The
    mode flag at offset 8 (written by read_lock / write_lock /
    try_read_lock / try_write_lock) selects the appropriate Release
    entry point. Per Microsoft documentation Windows has separate
    Release entry points for shared vs exclusive holders, and no
    introspection on the lock itself - the flag bridges the gap so
    rwlock_unlock preserves the Linux pilot's mode-agnostic API
    contract.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. memory_get_int64 from offset 8 - read the mode flag.
    2. If flag == 1: api_release_srwlock_exclusive.
    3. Otherwise:    api_release_srwlock_shared.
    The flag is reset implicitly by the next acquire - it carries the
    state of the most recent acquire only, which is exactly what
    rwlock_unlock needs.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One load + one branch + one library call: ~12 ns uncontended.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must hold the lock in the same mode as the most recent
    acquire (which is invariant under the documented locking contract).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mode_flag be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with handle, 8
    If mode_flag is equal to 1:
        proc windows_x86_64_api_release_srwlock_exclusive from WinAPI with handle
    Otherwise:
        proc windows_x86_64_api_release_srwlock_shared from WinAPI with handle
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rwlock_try_read_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking shared-mode acquire. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-tryacquiresrwlockshared)
    returns nonzero on success, zero if a writer holds or is queued.
    On success we record the mode flag as 0 (shared); on failure the
    flag remains untouched.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. api_try_acquire_srwlock_shared.
    2. If success (nonzero), memory_set_int64 at offset 8 to 0.
    3. Return the BOOLEAN.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time, no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let success be proc windows_x86_64_api_try_acquire_srwlock_shared from WinAPI with handle
    If success is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with handle, 8, 0
    End If
    Return success
End Process

Process called "rwlock_try_write_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking exclusive-mode acquire. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-tryacquiresrwlockexclusive)
    returns nonzero on success, zero if any contender holds or is queued
    (reader or writer). On success we record the mode flag as 1
    (exclusive); on failure the flag remains untouched.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. api_try_acquire_srwlock_exclusive.
    2. If success (nonzero), memory_set_int64 at offset 8 to 1.
    3. Return the BOOLEAN.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time, no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let success be proc windows_x86_64_api_try_acquire_srwlock_exclusive from WinAPI with handle
    If success is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with handle, 8, 1
    End If
    Return success
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Hardware Query - GetSystemInfo-based logical-processor count
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "hardware_concurrency" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the number of logical processors visible to the calling
    process. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/sysinfoapi/nf-sysinfoapi-getsysteminfo)
    GetSystemInfo fills a SYSTEM_INFO structure whose dwNumberOfProcessors
    field (offset 32 = 0x20 on 64-bit Windows) reports the logical
    processor count.

    On any failure (mmap or unexpected zero count) we return 1 - the
    Linux pilot makes the same defensive choice, and callers downstream
    of hardware_concurrency typically use the result as a worker-pool
    size and would deadlock if given 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. mmap a 64-byte buffer for the SYSTEM_INFO struct (the canonical
       layout is 48 bytes plus padding; 64 is the smallest aligned
       allocation that comfortably holds the struct).
    2. Zero the buffer (defensive - GetSystemInfo writes every field
       but we cannot rely on mmap's initial-zero guarantee across all
       backends).
    3. Invoke api_get_system_info on the buffer.
    4. Read dwNumberOfProcessors at offset 32 (DWORD = int32, but
       memory_get_int32 returns it as an Integer with the upper bits
       zero - exactly what we want).
    5. munmap the buffer.
    6. If the count is 0 or negative, return 1; otherwise return the
       count.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap + one near-zero GetSystemInfo (internally cached by
    kernel32) + one munmap. The result should be cached by callers
    above the primitive layer.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    GetSystemInfo is unrestricted; the SYSTEM_INFO buffer is process-
    private (MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let info_buf be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 64, 3, 34, -1, 0
    If info_buf is less than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Defensively zero the 64-byte buffer before the API populates it.
    Let zero_idx be 0
    While zero_idx is less than 64:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with info_buf, zero_idx, 0
        Set zero_idx to zero_idx plus 1
    End While

    proc windows_x86_64_api_get_system_info from WinAPI with info_buf

    Note: dwNumberOfProcessors at SYSTEM_INFO offset 32 (0x20) on 64-bit Windows.
    Let processor_count be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with info_buf, 32

    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with info_buf, 64

    If processor_count is less than 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return processor_count
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Thread Scheduling Priority and Affinity
Note: ============================================================================
Note:
Stubs for this platform. Implementing these requires the platform-specific
priority/affinity syscall surface (pthread_setschedparam on POSIX,
SetThreadPriority on Windows, etc.). The Linux x86_64 / ARM64 / ARM32
implementations exercise the real syscalls; other platforms surface a
deterministic failure to the caller (the higher-level thread_core API
already routes failure correctly to its return-1/return-0 contracts).
:End Note

Process called "thread_set_priority" takes handle as Integer, priority as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unimplemented on this platform; surface failure to the caller.
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "thread_get_priority" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unimplemented on this platform; return the -999 sentinel
    Note: expected by thread_core::thread_get_priority.
    Return 0 minus 999
End Process

Process called "thread_set_affinity" takes handle as Integer, cpu_mask as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unimplemented on this platform; surface failure to the caller.
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "thread_get_affinity" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unimplemented on this platform; return 0 mask (no CPUs known).
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "get_cpu_id" returns Integer:
    Note: Unimplemented on this platform; return -1 sentinel.
    Return 0 minus 1
End Process
